Its a great self service restaurant. The cashiers are nice and friendly, and you get an order of naan and yogurt with your order which is a great throwback if you’re Iranian. The food is decent, though their ground beef kabob (kabob koobideh) is not something to write home about. Their chicken kabob however is my favorite. Their salads are a little plain but their dressing is on point. Overall I’d say for a classic, chain, self service restaurant, they’re pretty good but I think they need to up their game a little if they wish to keep their good reputation given there are a lot of hip, modern fast food chains opening up in the area. Recommendations: Kashk e Badenjaan (eggplant dip) or the Shiraz salad for starters and Joojeh (chunk chicken breast) or Barreh (chunk lamb meat) kabob for entree.

We always stop by this chain restaurant (this specific location is our first time) when we are in the area but I believe this is our last time.  This restaurant used to be our favorite for good food, nice portions, fresh bread (Naan) and fast preparation. However, this is not the case anymore since the quality of food was very poor. We had the family platter number 1 as part of our order. The kubide (ground kebab) was dry a bit and fallen apart. The chenjeh was small pieces, very dry and mostly burned. The homemade doogh (yogurt drink) was watered down and not close to what a doogh should be.  In addition, I highly recommend you to check your order before leaving the restaurant. In my case, we had ordered an extra side of kubide (ground meat kebab), which it was missing. When I called, they confirmed that it was there and served (however we couldn’t find it😂). So I didn’t argue it further since it is partially my fault for not checking my order.  FYI, this is my review based on my past experiences with this restaurant. I understand this is a fast food version of what a Persian restaurant is, but they used to do a much better job.

It was so good that I actually thought about going again the next day. The kabob was moist and very flavorful, I'd definitely recommend it. The basmati rice was also tasty. I will be going back.

These are the core things you can expect from a Moby Dick's location: 1. Delicious food (try the Chenjeh - gorgeous marinated beef, try the saffron rice - light and fluffy and mix in that pat of butter and it's like a warm hug for each of your taste buds, you get the bread and yogurt sauce included and it's soft and tasty and the sauce is sightly tangy and on point) 2. Clean 3. Friendly and efficient staff 4. Slightly more expensive than fast food places but the food's on another level. 5. Many locations are open late so you can enjoy this amazing food after having too many drinks. The Bethesda location is where I randomly discovered Moby. It was 2002 and cell phones were dumb and so was I (well that hasn’t changed). I was just hungry after my screenwriting class. And I just randomly chose the Chenjeh and the rest is history. This location will always be first in my heart.
